# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: magnetometer-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A **compass** is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] It typically consists of a magnetized needle or another element, such as a compass card or compass rose, that pivots to align itself with magnetic north.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Other methods may be used, including gyroscopes, magnetometers, and GPS receivers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Compasses often show angles in degrees: north corresponds to 0°, and the angles increase clockwise, so east is 90°, south is 180°, and west is 270°.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] These numbers allow the compass to show azimuths or bearings which are commonly stated in degrees.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] If local variation between magnetic north and true north is known, then direction of magnetic north also gives direction of true north.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Among the Four Great Inventions, the magnetic compass was first invented as a device for divination as early as the Chinese Han dynasty (since c.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] 206 BC), and later adopted for navigation by the Song dynasty Chinese during the 11th century.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The first usage of a compass recorded in Western Europe occurred around 1190 and in the Islamic world in the 13th century.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The magnetic compass is the most familiar compass type.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] It functions as a pointer to "magnetic north", the local magnetic meridian, because the magnetized needle at its heart aligns itself with the horizontal component of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The magnetic field exerts a torque on the needle, pulling the North end or *pole* of the needle approximately toward the Earth's North magnetic pole, and pulling the other toward the Earth's South magnetic pole.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The needle is mounted on a low-friction pivot point, in better compasses a jewel bearing, so it can turn easily.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] When the compass is held level, the needle turns until, after a few seconds to allow oscillations to die out, it settles into its equilibrium orientation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] In navigation, directions on maps are usually expressed with reference to geographical or true north, the direction toward the Geographical North Pole, the rotation axis of the Earth.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Depending on where the compass is located on the surface of the Earth the angle between true north and magnetic north, called magnetic declination can vary widely with geographic location.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The local magnetic declination is given on most maps, to allow the map to be oriented with a compass parallel to true north.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The locations of the Earth's magnetic poles slowly change with time, which is referred to as geomagnetic secular variation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The effect of this means a map with the latest declination information should be used.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Some magnetic compasses include means to manually compensate for the magnetic declination, so that the compass shows true directions.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] One of the earliest known references to lodestone's magnetic properties was made by 6th century BC Greek philosopher Thales of Miletus, whom the ancient Greeks credited with discovering lodestone's attraction to iron and other lodestones.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The name *magnet* may come from lodestones found in Magnesia, Anatolia.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The ancient Indian medical text *Sushruta Samhita* describes using magnetic properties of the lodestone to remove arrows embedded in a person's body.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The earliest Chinese literary reference to magnetism occurs in the 4th-century BC *Book of the Devil Valley Master* (*Guiguzi*).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Some claims state that the first devices utilising lodestone's natural magnetic properties were in ancient Han dynasty China.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] When it is placed on a smooth bronze plate, the spoon would invariably rotate to a north–south axis.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] While this has been shown to work, archaeologists have yet to discover an actual spoon made of magnetite in a Han tomb.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The first compasses used for navigation appeared in China by 1088 during the Song dynasty, as described by Shen Kuo.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] These compasses were made of iron needles, magnetized by striking them with a lodestone.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Dry compasses began to appear around 1300 in Medieval Europe and the Islamic world.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This was supplanted in the early 20th century by the liquid-filled magnetic compass.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Some historians believe that a compass that used an iron fish to point north in a vessel of oil was use in 4th century Southern India, although others believe that evidence of compasses being used prior to the 11th century is very weak.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Modern compasses usually use a magnetized needle or dial inside a capsule completely filled with a liquid (lamp oil, mineral oil, white spirits, purified kerosene, or ethyl alcohol are common).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] While older designs commonly incorporated a flexible rubber diaphragm or airspace inside the capsule to allow for volume changes caused by temperature or altitude, some modern liquid compasses use smaller housings and/or flexible capsule materials to accomplish the same result.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The liquid inside the capsule serves to damp the movement of the needle, reducing oscillation time and increasing stability.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Key points on the compass, including the north end of the needle are often marked with phosphorescent, photoluminescent, or self-luminous materials to enable the compass to be read at night or in poor light.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] As the compass fill liquid is noncompressible under pressure, many ordinary liquid-filled compasses will operate accurately underwater to considerable depths.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Many modern compasses incorporate a baseplate and protractor tool, and are referred to variously as "orienteering", "baseplate", "map compass" or "protractor" designs.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This type of compass uses a separate magnetized needle inside a rotating capsule, an orienting "box" or gate for aligning the needle with magnetic north, a transparent base containing map orienting lines, and a bezel (outer dial) marked in degrees or other units of angular measurement.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The capsule is mounted in a transparent baseplate containing a *direction-of-travel* (DOT) indicator for use in taking bearings directly from a map.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The sport of orienteering has also resulted in the development of models with extremely fast-settling and stable needles utilizing rare-earth magnets for optimal use with a topographic map, a land navigation technique known as *terrain association*.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Many marine compasses designed for use on boats with constantly shifting angles use dampening fluids such as isopar M or isopar L to limit the rapid fluctuation and direction of the needle.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The military forces of a few nations, notably the United States Army, continue to issue field compasses with magnetized compass dials or cards instead of needles.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A magnetic card compass is usually equipped with an optical, lensatic, or prismatic sight, which allows the user to read the bearing or azimuth off the compass card while simultaneously aligning the compass with the objective (see photo).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Magnetic card compass designs normally require a separate protractor tool in order to take bearings directly from a map.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] M-1950 military lensatic compass does not use a liquid-filled capsule as a damping mechanism, but rather electromagnetic induction to control oscillation of its magnetized card.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A "deep-well" design is used to allow the compass to be used globally with a card tilt of up to 8 degrees without impairing accuracy.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] As induction forces provide less damping than fluid-filled designs, a needle lock is fitted to the compass to reduce wear, operated by the folding action of the rear sight/lens holder.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The use of air-filled induction compasses has declined over the years, as they may become inoperative or inaccurate in freezing temperatures or extremely humid environments due to condensation or water ingress.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] M-1950 (Cammenga 3H) military lensatic compass, the Silva 4b *Militaire*, and the Suunto M-5N(T) contain the radioactive material tritium (3 1H) and a combination of phosphors.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] M-1950 equipped with self-luminous lighting contains 120 mCi (millicuries) of tritium.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The purpose of the tritium and phosphors is to provide illumination for the compass, via radioluminescent tritium illumination, which does not require the compass to be "recharged" by sunlight or artificial light.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] However, tritium has a half-life of only about 12 years, so a compass that contains 120 mCi of tritium when new will contain only 60 when it is 12 years old, 30 when it is 24 years old, and so on.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Consequently, the illumination of the display will fade.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Mariners' compasses can have two or more magnets permanently attached to a compass card, which moves freely on a pivot.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A *lubber line*, which can be a marking on the compass bowl or a small fixed needle, indicates the ship's heading on the compass card.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Traditionally the card is divided into thirty-two points (known as *rhumbs*), although modern compasses are marked in degrees rather than cardinal points.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The glass-covered box (or bowl) contains a suspended gimbal within a binnacle.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The magnetic compass is very reliable at moderate latitudes, but in geographic regions near the Earth's magnetic poles it becomes unusable.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] As the compass is moved closer to one of the magnetic poles, the magnetic declination, the difference between the direction to geographical north and magnetic north, becomes greater and greater.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] At some point close to the magnetic pole the compass will not indicate any particular direction but will begin to drift.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Also, the needle starts to point up or down when getting closer to the poles, because of the so-called magnetic inclination.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Cheap compasses with bad bearings may get stuck because of this and therefore indicate a wrong direction.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Magnetic compasses are influenced by any fields other than Earth's.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Local environments may contain magnetic mineral deposits and artificial sources such as MRIs, large iron or steel bodies, electrical engines or strong permanent magnets.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Any electrically conductive body produces its own magnetic field when it is carrying an electric current.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Magnetic compasses are prone to errors in the neighborhood of such bodies.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Some compasses include magnets which can be adjusted to compensate for external magnetic fields, making the compass more reliable and accurate.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A compass is also subject to errors when the compass is accelerated or decelerated in an airplane or automobile.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Depending on which of the Earth's hemispheres the compass is located and if the force is acceleration or deceleration the compass will increase or decrease the indicated heading.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Compasses that include compensating magnets are especially prone to these errors, since accelerations tilt the needle, bringing it closer or further from the magnets.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Another error of the mechanical compass is the turning error.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] When one turns from a heading of east or west the compass will lag behind the turn or lead ahead of the turn.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Magnetometers, and substitutes such as gyrocompasses, are more stable in such situations.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A thumb compass is a type of compass commonly used in orienteering, a sport in which map reading and terrain association are paramount.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Consequently, most thumb compasses have minimal or no degree markings at all, and are normally used only to orient the map to magnetic north.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] An oversized rectangular needle or north indicator aids visibility.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Thumb compasses are also often transparent so that an orienteer can hold a map in the hand with the compass and see the map through the compass.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The best models use rare-earth magnets to reduce needle settling time to 1 second or less.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The earth inductor compass (or "induction compass") determines directions using the principle of electromagnetic induction, with the Earth's magnetic field acting as the induction field for an electric generator, the measurable output of which varies depending on orientation .
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A vertical card magnetic compass installed in an airplane can eliminate some magnetic dipping errors while making the compass less confusing to read in the cockpit.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The compass dial is driven by a set of gears controlled by a magnet mounted on a shaft.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Eddy current induced into a damping cup also helps mitigate magnet oscillation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Small electronic compasses (eCompasses) found in clocks, mobile phones, and other electronic devices are solid-state microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) compasses, usually built out of two or three magnetic field sensors that provide data for a microprocessor.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Often, the device is a discrete component which outputs either a digital or analog signal proportional to its orientation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This signal is interpreted by a controller or microprocessor and either used internally, or sent to a display unit.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The sensor uses highly calibrated internal electronics to measure the response of the device to the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Apart from navigational compasses, other specialty compasses have also been designed to accommodate specific uses.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A magnetic rod is required when constructing a compass.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This can be created by aligning an iron or steel rod with Earth's magnetic field and then tempering or striking it.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] However, this method produces only a weak magnet, so other methods are preferred.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] For example, a magnetised rod can be created by repeatedly rubbing an iron rod with a magnetic lodestone.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This magnetised rod (or magnetic needle) is then placed on a low-friction surface to allow it to freely pivot to align itself with the magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] It is then labeled so the user can distinguish the north-pointing from the south-pointing end; in modern convention the north end is typically marked in some way.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] If a needle is rubbed on a lodestone or other magnet, the needle becomes magnetized.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] When it is inserted in a cork or piece of wood, and placed in a bowl of water it becomes a compass.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Such devices were universally used as compasses until the invention of the box-like compass with a "dry" pivoting needle, sometime around 1300.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Originally, many compasses were marked only as to the direction of magnetic north, or to the four cardinal points (north, south, east, west).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Later, these were divided, in China into 24, and in Europe into 32 equally spaced points around the compass card.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] For a table of the thirty-two points, see compass points.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] In the modern era, the 360-degree system took hold.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This system is still in use today for civilian navigators.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The degree system spaces 360 equidistant points located clockwise around the compass dial.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] In the 19th century some European nations adopted the "grad" (also called grade or gon) system instead, where a right angle is 100 grads to give a circle of 400 grads.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Dividing grads into tenths to give a circle of 4000 decigrades has also been used in armies.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Most military forces have adopted the French "millieme" system.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This is an approximation of a milli-radian (6283 per circle), in which the compass dial is spaced into 6400 units or "mils" for additional precision when measuring angles, laying artillery, etc.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The value to the military is that one angular mil subtends approximately one metre at a distance of one kilometer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Imperial Russia used a system derived by dividing the circumference of a circle into chords of the same length as the radius.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Each of these was divided into 100 spaces, giving a circle of 600.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The Soviet Union divided these into tenths to give a circle of 6000 units, usually translated as "mils".
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This system was adopted by the former Warsaw Pact countries, *e.g.*, the Soviet Union, East Germany, etc., often counterclockwise (see picture of wrist compass).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Because the Earth's magnetic field's inclination and intensity vary at different latitudes, compasses are often balanced during manufacture so that the dial or needle will be level, eliminating needle drag.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Most manufacturers balance their compass needles for one of five zones, ranging from zone 1, covering most of the Northern Hemisphere, to zone 5 covering Australia and the southern oceans.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This individual zone balancing prevents excessive dipping of one end of the needle, which can cause the compass card to stick and give false readings.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Some compasses feature a special needle balancing system that will accurately indicate magnetic north regardless of the particular magnetic zone.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Other magnetic compasses have a small sliding counterweight installed on the needle.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This sliding counterweight, called a "rider", can be used for counterbalancing the needle against the dip caused by inclination if the compass is taken to a zone with a higher or lower dip.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Like any magnetic device, compasses are affected by nearby ferrous materials, as well as by strong local electromagnetic forces.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Compasses used for wilderness land navigation should not be used in proximity to ferrous metal objects or electromagnetic fields (car electrical systems, automobile engines, steel pitons, etc.) as that can affect their accuracy.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Compasses are particularly difficult to use accurately in or near trucks, cars or other mechanized vehicles even when corrected for deviation by the use of built-in magnets or other devices.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Large amounts of ferrous metal combined with the on-and-off electrical fields caused by the vehicle's ignition and charging systems generally result in significant compass errors.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] At sea, a ship's compass must also be corrected for errors, called deviation, caused by iron and steel in its structure and equipment.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The ship is *swung*, that is rotated about a fixed point while its heading is noted by alignment with fixed points on the shore.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A compass deviation card is prepared so that the navigator can convert between compass and magnetic headings.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The compass can be corrected in three ways.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] First the lubber line can be adjusted so that it is aligned with the direction in which the ship travels, then the effects of permanent magnets can be corrected for by small magnets fitted within the case of the compass.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The effect of ferromagnetic materials in the compass's environment can be corrected by two iron balls mounted on either side of the compass binnacle in concert with permanent magnets and a Flinders bar.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The coefficient $a_{0}$ represents the error in the lubber line, while $a_{1},b_{1}$ the ferromagnetic effects and $a_{2},b_{2}$ the non-ferromagnetic component.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A similar process is used to calibrate the compass in light general aviation aircraft, with the compass deviation card often mounted permanently just above or below the magnetic compass on the instrument panel.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Fluxgate electronic compasses can be calibrated automatically, and can also be programmed with the correct local compass variation so as to indicate the true heading.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A magnetic compass points to magnetic north pole, which is approximately 1,000 miles from the true geographic North Pole.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A magnetic compass's user can determine true North by finding the magnetic north and then correcting for variation and deviation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Variation is defined as the angle between the direction of true (geographic) north and the direction of the meridian between the magnetic poles.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Variation values for most of the oceans had been calculated and published by 1914.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Deviation refers to the response of the compass to local magnetic fields caused by the presence of iron and electric currents; one can partly compensate for these by careful location of the compass and the placement of compensating magnets under the compass itself.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Mariners have long known that these measures do not completely cancel deviation; hence, they performed an additional step by measuring the compass bearing of a landmark with a known magnetic bearing.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] They then pointed their ship to the next compass point and measured again, graphing their results.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] In this way, correction tables could be created, which would be consulted when compasses were used when traveling in those locations.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Mariners are concerned about very accurate measurements; however, casual users need not be concerned with differences between magnetic and true North.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Except in areas of extreme magnetic declination variance (20 degrees or more), this is enough to protect from walking in a substantially different direction than expected over short distances, provided the terrain is fairly flat and visibility is not impaired.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] By carefully recording distances (time or paces) and magnetic bearings traveled, one can plot a course and return to one's starting point using the compass alone.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Compass navigation in conjunction with a map (*terrain association*) requires a different method.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The orienting lines in the base of the compass dial are then rotated to align with actual or true north by aligning them with a marked line of longitude (or the vertical margin of the map), ignoring the compass needle entirely.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The resulting *true bearing* or map bearing may then be read at the degree indicator or direction-of-travel (DOT) line, which may be followed as an *azimuth* (course) to the destination.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] If a *magnetic* north bearing or *compass bearing* is desired, the compass must be adjusted by the amount of magnetic declination before using the bearing so that both map and compass are in agreement.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] In the given example, the large mountain in the second photo was selected as the target destination on the map.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Some compasses allow the scale to be adjusted to compensate for the local magnetic declination; if adjusted correctly, the compass will give the true bearing instead of the magnetic bearing.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The modern hand-held protractor compass always has an additional direction-of-travel (DOT) arrow or indicator inscribed on the baseplate.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] To check one's progress along a course or azimuth, or to ensure that the object in view is indeed the destination, a new compass reading may be taken to the target if visible (here, the large mountain).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] After pointing the DOT arrow on the baseplate at the target, the compass is oriented so that the needle is superimposed over the orienting arrow in the capsule.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The resulting bearing indicated is the magnetic bearing to the target.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Again, if one is using "true" or map bearings, and the compass does not have preset, pre-adjusted declination, one must additionally add or subtract magnetic declination to convert the *magnetic bearing* into a *true bearing*.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The exact value of the magnetic declination is place-dependent and varies over time, though declination is frequently given on the map itself or obtainable on-line from various sites.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] If the hiker has been following the correct path, the compass' corrected (true) indicated bearing should closely correspond to the true bearing previously obtained from the map.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A compass should be laid down on a level surface so that the needle only rests or hangs on the bearing fused to the compass casing – if used at a tilt, the needle might touch the casing on the compass and not move freely, hence not pointing to the magnetic north accurately, giving a faulty reading.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] To see if the needle is well leveled, look closely at the needle, and tilt it slightly to see if the needle is swaying side to side freely and the needle is not contacting the casing of the compass.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] If the needle tilts to one direction, tilt the compass slightly and gently to the opposing direction until the compass needle is horizontal, lengthwise.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Items to avoid around compasses are magnets of any kind and any electronics.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Magnetic fields from electronics can easily disrupt the needle, preventing it from aligning with the Earth's magnetic fields, causing inaccurate readings.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The Earth's natural magnetic forces are considerably weak, measuring at 0.5 gauss and magnetic fields from household electronics can easily exceed it, overpowering the compass needle.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Exposure to strong magnets, or magnetic interference can sometimes cause the magnetic poles of the compass needle to differ or even reverse.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Avoid iron rich deposits when using a compass, for example, certain rocks which contain magnetic minerals, like Magnetite.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] This is often indicated by a rock with a surface which is dark and has a metallic luster, not all magnetic mineral bearing rocks have this indication.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] To see if a rock or an area is causing interference on a compass, get out of the area, and see if the needle on the compass moves.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] If it does, it means that the area or rock the compass was previously at is causing interference and should be avoided.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] There are other ways to find north than the use of magnetism, and from a navigational point of view a total of seven possible ways exist (where magnetism is one of the seven).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Two sensors that use two of the remaining six principles are often also called compasses, i.e. the gyrocompass and GPS-compass.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] A gyrocompass is similar to a gyroscope.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] It is a non-magnetic compass that finds true north by using an (electrically powered) fast-spinning wheel and friction forces in order to exploit the rotation of the Earth.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Large ships typically rely on a gyrocompass, using the magnetic compass only as a backup.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Increasingly, electronic fluxgate compasses are used on smaller vessels.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] However, magnetic compasses are still widely in use as they can be small, use simple reliable technology, are comparatively cheap, are often easier to use than GPS, require no energy supply, and unlike GPS, are not affected by objects, e.g. trees, that can block the reception of electronic signals.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] GPS receivers using two or more antennae mounted separately and blending the data with an inertial motion unit (IMU) can now achieve 0.02° in heading accuracy and have startup times in seconds rather than hours for gyrocompass systems.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] The devices accurately determine the positions (latitudes, longitudes and altitude) of the antennae on the Earth, from which the cardinal directions can be calculated.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Manufactured primarily for maritime and aviation applications, they can also detect pitch and roll of ships.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Small, portable GPS receivers with only a single antenna can also determine directions if they are being moved, even if only at walking pace.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] By accurately determining its position on the Earth at times a few seconds apart, the device can calculate its speed and the true bearing (relative to *true north*) of its direction of motion.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Frequently, it is preferable to measure the direction in which a vehicle is actually moving, rather than its heading, i.e. the direction in which its nose is pointing.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] These directions may be different if there is a crosswind or tidal current.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] GPS compasses share the main advantages of gyrocompasses.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] They determine true North, as opposed to magnetic North, and they are unaffected by perturbations of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Additionally, compared with gyrocompasses, they are much cheaper, they work better in polar regions, they are less prone to be affected by mechanical vibration, and they can be initialized far more quickly.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] However, they depend on the functioning of, and communication with, the GPS satellites, which might be disrupted by an electronic attack or by the effects of a severe solar storm.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/compass] Gyrocompasses remain in use for military purposes (especially in submarines, where magnetic and GPS compasses are useless), but have been largely superseded by GPS compasses, with magnetic backups, in civilian contexts.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A **magnetometer** is a device that measures magnetic field (**B**) or magnetic dipole moment.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Different types of magnetometers measure the direction, strength, or relative change of the magnetic **B**-field at a particular location.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A compass is one such device, one that measures the direction of an ambient magnetic field, in this case, the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Other magnetometers measure the magnetic dipole moment of a magnetic material such as a ferromagnet, for example by recording the effect of this magnetic dipole on the induced current in a coil.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The invention of the magnetometer is usually credited to Carl Friedrich Gauss in 1832.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Earlier, more primitive instruments were developed by Christopher Hansteen in 1819, and by William Scoresby by 1823.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetometers are widely used for measuring the Earth's magnetic field, in geophysical surveys, to detect magnetic anomalies of various types, and to determine the dipole moment of magnetic materials.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In an aircraft's attitude and heading reference system, they are commonly used as a heading reference.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetometers are also used by the military as a triggering mechanism in magnetic mines to detect submarines.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Consequently, some countries, such as the United States, Canada and Australia, classify the more sensitive magnetometers as military technology, and control their distribution.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetometers can be used as metal detectors: they can detect only ferromagnetic metals, but can detect such metals at a much greater distance than conventional metal detectors, which rely on conductivity.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetometers are capable of detecting large objects, such as cars, at over 10 metres (33 ft), while a conventional metal detector's range is rarely more than 2 metres (7 ft).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In recent years, magnetometers have been miniaturized to the extent that they can be incorporated in integrated circuits at very low cost and are finding increasing use as miniaturized compasses (MEMS magnetic field sensor).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetic fields are vector quantities characterized by both strength and direction.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The strength of a magnetic field, **B**, is measured with the unit tesla in the SI units, and in gauss in the cgs system of units.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Measurements of the Earth's magnetic field are often quoted in the unit nanotesla (nT), also called a gamma.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The Earth's magnetic field can vary from 20000 to 80000 nT depending on location, fluctuations in the Earth's magnetic field are on the order of 100 nT, and magnetic field variations due to magnetic anomalies can be in the picotesla (pT) range.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] *Gaussmeters* and *teslameters* are magnetometers that measure in the unit gauss or tesla, respectively.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In some contexts, magnetometer is the term used for an instrument that measures fields of less than 1 millitesla (mT) and gaussmeter is used for those measuring greater than 1 mT.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] There are two basic types of magnetometer measurement.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] *Vector magnetometers* measure the vector components of a magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] *Total field magnetometers* or *scalar magnetometers* measure the magnitude of the vector magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetometers may also be classified by their situation or intended use.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] *Stationary magnetometers* are installed to a fixed position and measurements are taken while the magnetometer is stationary.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] *Portable* or *mobile magnetometers* are meant to be used while in motion and may be manually carried or transported in a moving vehicle.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] *Laboratory magnetometers* are used to measure the magnetic field of materials placed within them and are typically stationary.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] *Survey magnetometers* are used to measure magnetic fields in geomagnetic surveys; they may be fixed base stations, as in the INTERMAGNET network, or mobile magnetometers used to scan a geographic region.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] An early adoption (in the 1950s) of airborne magnetometry by Inco prompted the discovery of nickel ore deposits that led to the founding of Thompson, Manitoba.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The performance and capabilities of magnetometers are described through their technical specifications.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The compass, consisting of a magnetized needle whose orientation changes in response to the ambient magnetic field, is a simple type of magnetometer, one that measures the direction of the field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In 1823 William Scoresby (1789-1857), an English explorer, scientist and clergyman, was deeply involved in magnetic science, particularly in improving ships' compasses.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In 1833, Carl Friedrich Gauss, head of the Geomagnetic Observatory in Göttingen, published a paper on measurement of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] It described a new instrument that consisted of a permanent bar magnet suspended horizontally from a gold fibre.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The difference in the oscillations when the bar was magnetised and when it was demagnetised allowed Gauss to calculate an absolute value for the strength of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The gauss, the CGS unit of magnetic flux density was named in his honour, defined as one maxwell per square centimeter, which corresponds to 10−4 tesla (the SI unit).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Francis Ronalds and Charles Brooke independently invented magnetographs in 1846 that continuously recorded the magnet's movements using photography, thus easing the load on observers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] They were quickly utilised by Edward Sabine and others in a global magnetic survey and updated machines were in use well into the 20th century.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Laboratory magnetometers measure the magnetization, also known as the magnetic moment of a sample material.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Unlike survey magnetometers, laboratory magnetometers require the sample to be placed inside the magnetometer, and often the temperature, magnetic field, and other parameters of the sample can be controlled.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A sample's magnetization, is primarily dependent on the ordering of unpaired electrons within its atoms, with smaller contributions from nuclear magnetic moments, Langevin diamagnetism, among others.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Ordering of magnetic moments are primarily classified as diamagnetic, paramagnetic, ferromagnetic, or antiferromagnetic (although the zoology of magnetic ordering also includes ferrimagnetic, helimagnetic, toroidal, spin glass, etc.).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Measuring the magnetization as a function of temperature and magnetic field can give clues as to the type of magnetic ordering, as well as any phase transitions between different types of magnetic orders that occur at critical temperatures or magnetic fields.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This type of magnetometry measurement is very important to understand the magnetic properties of materials in physics, chemistry, geophysics and geology, as well as sometimes biology.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] SQUID magnetometers are a type of tool used both as survey and as laboratory magnetometers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] It is based on the concept of flux quantization in a superconducting loop.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] SQUID magnetometry is an extremely sensitive absolute magnetometry technique, reproducibly achieving femtotesla resolutions in optimized laboratory settings.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] However SQUIDs are noise sensitive, making them impractical as laboratory magnetometers in high DC magnetic fields, and in pulsed magnets.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The necessity to keep at least part of the setup (the superconducting elements) to be cooled to cryogenic temperatures limits the applications as the sensor can not be brought arbitrarily close to the field source.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Commercial SQUID magnetometers are available for sample temperatures between 300 mK and 400 K, and magnetic fields up to 7 T.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Inductive pickup coils (also referred as inductive sensor) measure the magnetic dipole moment of a material by detecting the current induced in a coil due to the changing magnetic moment of the sample.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The sample's magnetization can be changed by applying a small ac magnetic field (or a rapidly changing dc field), as occurs in capacitor-driven pulsed magnets.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] These measurements require differentiating between the magnetic field produced by the sample and that from the external applied field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Often a special arrangement of cancellation coils is used.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] For example, half of the pickup coil is wound in one direction, and the other half in the other direction, and the sample is placed in only one half.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The external uniform magnetic field is detected by both halves of the coil, and since they are counter-wound, the external magnetic field produces no net signal.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Vibrating-sample magnetometers (VSMs) detect the dipole moment of a sample by mechanically vibrating the sample inside of an inductive pickup coil or inside of a SQUID coil.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Induced current or changing flux in the coil is measured.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The vibration is typically created by a motor or a piezoelectric actuator.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Typically the VSM technique is about an order of magnitude less sensitive than SQUID magnetometry.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] VSMs can be combined with SQUIDs to create a system that is more sensitive than either one alone.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Heat due to the sample vibration can limit the base temperature of a VSM, typically to 2 K.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] VSM is also impractical for measuring a fragile sample that is sensitive to rapid acceleration.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Pulsed-field magnetometry is another method making use of pickup coils to measure magnetization.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Unlike VSMs where the sample is physically vibrated, in pulsed-field magnetometry, the sample is secured and the external magnetic field is changed rapidly, for example in a capacitor-driven magnet.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] One of multiple techniques must then be used to cancel out the external field from the field produced by the sample.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] These include counterwound coils that cancel the external uniform field and background measurements with the sample removed from the coil.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetic torque magnetometry can be even more sensitive than SQUID magnetometry.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] However, magnetic torque magnetometry doesn't measure magnetism directly as all the previously mentioned methods do.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetic torque magnetometry instead measures the torque τ acting on a sample's magnetic moment *μ* as a result of a uniform magnetic field *B*, *τ* = *μ* × *B*.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A torque is thus a measure of the sample's magnetic or shape anisotropy.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In some cases the sample's magnetization can be extracted from the measured torque.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In other cases, the magnetic torque measurement is used to detect magnetic phase transitions or quantum oscillations.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Faraday force magnetometry uses the fact that a spatial magnetic field gradient produces force that acts on a magnetized object, *F* = (*M*⋅∇)*B*.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In Faraday force magnetometry the force on the sample can be measured by a scale (hanging the sample from a sensitive balance), or by detecting the displacement against a spring.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Commonly a capacitive load cell or cantilever is used because of its sensitivity, size, and lack of mechanical parts.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Faraday force magnetometry is approximately one order of magnitude less sensitive than a SQUID.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The biggest drawback to Faraday force magnetometry is that it requires some means of not only producing a magnetic field, but also producing a magnetic field gradient.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] While this can be accomplished by using a set of special pole faces, a much better result can be achieved by using set of gradient coils.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A major advantage to Faraday force magnetometry is that it is small and reasonably tolerant to noise, and thus can be implemented in a wide range of environments, including a dilution refrigerator.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Faraday force magnetometry can also be complicated by the presence of torque (see previous technique).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This can be circumvented by varying the gradient field independently of the applied DC field so the torque and the Faraday force contribution can be separated, and/or by designing a Faraday force magnetometer that prevents the sample from being rotated.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Optical magnetometry makes use of various optical techniques to measure magnetization.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] One such technique, Kerr magnetometry makes use of the magneto-optic Kerr effect, or MOKE.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In this technique, incident light is directed at the sample's surface.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Light interacts with a magnetized surface nonlinearly so the reflected light has an elliptical polarization, which is then measured by a detector.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Another method of optical magnetometry is Faraday rotation magnetometry.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Faraday rotation magnetometry utilizes nonlinear magneto-optical rotation to measure a sample's magnetization.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In this method a Faraday modulating thin film is applied to the sample to be measured and a series of images are taken with a camera that senses the polarization of the reflected light.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] To reduce noise, multiple pictures are then averaged together.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] One advantage to this method is that it allows mapping of the magnetic characteristics over the surface of a sample.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This can be especially useful when studying such things as the Meissner effect on superconductors.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Microfabricated optically pumped magnetometers (μOPMs) can be used to detect the origin of brain seizures more precisely and generate less heat than currently available SQUIDs.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The device works by using polarized light to control the spin of rubidium atoms which can be used to measure and monitor the magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Susceptometry, while not technicallly magnetometry, is a closely related technique to those above.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] It measures the magnetic suscpetibility *χ* *= dM/dH* instead of the magnetization *M*.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This is particularly relevant when (instead of a static) a dynamic magnetic field *H*(*t*) is applied to the sample in order to investigate its *dynamic* magnetic properties.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In the mathematically simplest case, a sinusoidal excitation field *h*(*t*) = *h0*sin(2*πt*) is overlaid onto a constant (possibly zero) magnetic field *H*: *H*(*t*) = *H0* + *h*(*t*).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The resulting time-dependent magnetization *M*(*t*) can be decomposed into a series of harmonics.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] *χ'1* and *χ''1* are commonly referred to as *the* a.c. magnetic suscpetibilities, where *χ'1* is the reactive/in-phase component and *χ''1* is the absorptive/out-of-phase component.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This technique can for example be used to gain an insight on the magnetic phase transitions or the freezing behavior of spin glasses.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] At a close to an ordering point, the spin dynamics will exhibit a critical slowing down, which means the absorptive component *χ''1* peaks (see the Debye relaxor model in dielectrics).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A.C. susceptometry may also be used as a more convenient probe to determine the static magnetic susceptibility.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] For this, the frequency *f* is chosen to be smaller than the spin dynamics.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A dipole in a gradient magnetic field experiences a net force.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The strength of the force can be measured and is proportional to the magnetic moment of the dipole.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] By alternating the gradient of the field and using a lock-in amplifier, a low noise floor can be achieved.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A vector is a mathematical entity with both magnitude and direction.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The Earth's magnetic field at a given point is a vector.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A magnetic compass is designed to give a horizontal bearing direction, whereas a *vector magnetometer* measures both the magnitude and direction of the total magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Three orthogonal sensors are required to measure the components of the magnetic field in all three dimensions.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] They are also rated as "absolute" if the strength of the field can be calibrated from their own known internal constants or "relative" if they need to be calibrated by reference to a known field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A *magnetograph* is a magnetometer that continuously records data over time.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This data is typically represented in magnetograms.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetometers can also be classified as "AC" if they measure fields that vary relatively rapidly in time (> 100 Hz), and "DC" if they measure fields that vary only slowly (quasi-static) or are static.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] AC magnetometers find use in electromagnetic systems (such as magnetotellurics), and DC magnetometers are used for detecting mineralisation and corresponding geological structures.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A direct current flowing in a solenoid creates a strong magnetic field around a hydrogen-rich fluid (kerosene and decane are popular, and even water can be used), causing some of the protons to align themselves with that field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The current is then interrupted, and as protons realign themselves with the ambient magnetic field, they precess at a frequency that is directly proportional to the magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This produces a weak rotating magnetic field that is picked up by a (sometimes separate) inductor, amplified electronically, and fed to a digital frequency counter whose output is typically scaled and displayed directly as field strength or output as digital data.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] For hand/backpack carried units, PPM sample rates are typically limited to less than one sample per second.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Measurements are typically taken with the sensor held at fixed locations at approximately 10 metre increments.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Portable instruments are also limited by sensor volume (weight) and power consumption.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] PPMs work in field gradients up to 3,000 nT/m, which is adequate for most mineral exploration work.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] For higher gradient tolerance, such as mapping banded iron formations and detecting large ferrous objects, Overhauser magnetometers can handle 10000 nT/m, and caesium magnetometers can handle 30000 nT/m.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] They are relatively inexpensive (< US$8,000) and were once widely used in mineral exploration.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Three manufacturers dominate the market: GEM Systems, Geometrics and Scintrex.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] For mineral exploration, they have been superseded by Overhauser, caesium, and potassium instruments, all of which are fast-cycling, and do not require the operator to pause between readings.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The *Overhauser effect magnetometer* or *Overhauser magnetometer* uses the same fundamental effect as the *proton precession magnetometer* to take measurements.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] By adding free radicals to the measurement fluid, the nuclear Overhauser effect can be exploited to significantly improve upon the proton precession magnetometer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Rather than aligning the protons using a solenoid, a low power radio-frequency field is used to align (polarise) the electron spin of the free radicals, which then couples to the protons via the Overhauser effect.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This has two main advantages: driving the RF field takes a fraction of the energy (allowing lighter-weight batteries for portable units), and faster sampling as the electron-proton coupling can happen even as measurements are being taken.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] An Overhauser magnetometer produces readings with a 0.01 nT to 0.02 nT standard deviation while sampling once per second.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The *optically pumped caesium vapour magnetometer* is a highly sensitive (300 fT/Hz0.5) and accurate device used in a wide range of applications.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] It is one of a number of alkali vapours (including rubidium and potassium) that are used in this way.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The device broadly consists of a photon emitter, such as a laser, an absorption chamber containing caesium vapour mixed with a "buffer gas" through which the emitted photons pass, and a photon detector, arranged in that order.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The buffer gas is usually helium or nitrogen and they are used to reduce collisions between the caesium vapour atoms.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The basic principle that allows the device to operate is the fact that a caesium atom can exist in any of nine energy levels, which can be informally thought of as the placement of electron atomic orbitals around the atomic nucleus.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] When a caesium atom within the chamber encounters a photon from the laser, it is excited to a higher energy state, emits a photon and falls to an indeterminate lower energy state.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The caesium atom is "sensitive" to the photons from the laser in three of its nine energy states, and therefore, assuming a closed system, all the atoms eventually fall into a state in which all the photons from the laser pass through unhindered and are measured by the photon detector.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The caesium vapour has become transparent.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This process happens continuously to maintain as many of the electrons as possible in that state.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] At this point, the sample (or population) is said to have been optically pumped and ready for measurement to take place.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] When an external field is applied it disrupts this state and causes atoms to move to different states which makes the vapour less transparent.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The photo detector can measure this change and therefore measure the magnitude of the magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In the most common type of caesium magnetometer, a very small AC magnetic field is applied to the cell.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Since the difference in the energy levels of the electrons is determined by the external magnetic field, there is a frequency at which this small AC field makes the electrons change states.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In this new state, the electrons once again can absorb a photon of light.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This causes a signal on a photo detector that measures the light passing through the cell.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The associated electronics use this fact to create a signal exactly at the frequency that corresponds to the external field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Another type of caesium magnetometer modulates the light applied to the cell.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This is referred to as a Bell-Bloom magnetometer, after the two scientists who first investigated the effect.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] If the light is turned on and off at the frequency corresponding to the Earth's field, there is a change in the signal seen at the photo detector.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Again, the associated electronics use this to create a signal exactly at the frequency that corresponds to the external field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Both methods lead to high performance magnetometers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Potassium is the only optically pumped magnetometer that operates on a single, narrow electron spin resonance (ESR) line in contrast to other alkali vapour magnetometers that use irregular, composite and wide spectral lines and helium with the inherently wide spectral line.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetometers based on helium-4 excited to its metastable triplet state thanks to a plasma discharge have been developed in the 1960s and 1970s by Texas Instruments, then by its spinoff Polatomic, and from late 1980s by CEA-Leti.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The latter pioneered a configuration which cancels the dead-zones, which are a recurrent problem of atomic magnetometers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This configuration was demonstrated to show an accuracy of 50 pT in orbit operation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The ESA chose this technology for the Swarm mission, which was launched in 2013.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] An experimental vector mode, which could compete with fluxgate magnetometers was tested in this mission with overall success.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The caesium and potassium magnetometers are typically used where a higher performance magnetometer than the proton magnetometer is needed.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In archaeology and geophysics, where the sensor sweeps through an area and many accurate magnetic field measurements are often needed, caesium and potassium magnetometers have advantages over the proton magnetometer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The caesium and potassium magnetometer's faster measurement rate allows the sensor to be moved through the area more quickly for a given number of data points.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Caesium and potassium magnetometers are insensitive to rotation of the sensor while the measurement is being made.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The lower noise of caesium and potassium magnetometers allow those measurements to more accurately show the variations in the field with position.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Vector magnetometers measure one or more components of the magnetic field electronically.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Using three orthogonal magnetometers, both azimuth and dip (inclination) can be measured.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] By taking the square root of the sum of the squares of the components the total magnetic field strength (also called total magnetic intensity, TMI) can be calculated by the Pythagorean theorem.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Vector magnetometers are subject to temperature drift and the dimensional instability of the ferrite cores.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] They also require leveling to obtain component information, unlike total field (scalar) instruments.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] For these reasons they are no longer used for mineral exploration.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The magnetic field induces a sine wave in a rotating coil.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The amplitude of the signal is proportional to the strength of the field, provided it is uniform, and to the sine of the angle between the rotation axis of the coil and the field lines.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The most common magnetic sensing devices are solid-state Hall effect sensors.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] These sensors produce a voltage proportional to the applied magnetic field and also sense polarity.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] They are used in applications where the magnetic field strength is relatively large, such as in anti-lock braking systems in cars, which sense wheel rotation speed via slots in the wheel disks.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] These are made of thin strips of Permalloy, a high magnetic permeability, nickel-iron alloy, whose electrical resistance varies with a change in magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] They have a well-defined axis of sensitivity, can be produced in 3-D versions and can be mass-produced as an integrated circuit.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] They have a response time of less than 1 microsecond and can be sampled in moving vehicles up to 1000 times/second.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] They can be used in compasses that read within 1°, for which the underlying sensor must reliably resolve 0.1°.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A fluxgate magnetometer consists of a small magnetically susceptible core wrapped by two coils of wire.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] An alternating electric current is passed through one coil, driving the core through an alternating cycle of magnetic saturation; i.e., magnetised, unmagnetised, inversely magnetised, unmagnetised, magnetised, and so forth.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This constantly changing field induces a voltage in the second coil which is measured by a detector.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In a magnetically neutral background, the input and output signals match.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] However, when the core is exposed to a background field, it is more easily saturated in alignment with that field and less easily saturated in opposition to it.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Hence the alternating magnetic field and the induced output voltage, are out of step with the input current.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The extent to which this is the case depends on the strength of the background magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Often, the signal in the output coil is integrated, yielding an output analog voltage proportional to the magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The fluxgate magnetometer was invented by H.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A team at Gulf Research Laboratories led by Victor Vacquier developed airborne fluxgate magnetometers to detect submarines during World War II and after the war confirmed the theory of plate tectonics by using them to measure shifts in the magnetic patterns on the sea floor.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A wide variety of sensors are currently available and used to measure magnetic fields.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Fluxgate compasses and gradiometers measure the direction and magnitude of magnetic fields.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Fluxgates are affordable, rugged and compact with miniaturization recently advancing to the point of complete sensor solutions in the form of IC chips, including examples from both academia and industry.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This, plus their typically low power consumption makes them ideal for a variety of sensing applications.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Gradiometers are commonly used for archaeological prospecting, and unexploded ordnance (UXO) detection such as the German military's popular *Foerster*.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Utility location specialists also use gradiometers for locating underground utilities such as pipeline valves, septic tanks, and manhole covers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The typical fluxgate magnetometer consists of a "sense" (secondary) coil surrounding an inner "drive" (primary) coil that is closely wound around a highly permeable core material, such as mu-metal or permalloy.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] An alternating current is applied to the drive winding, which drives the core in a continuous repeating cycle of saturation and unsaturation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] To an external field, the core is alternately weakly permeable and highly permeable.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The core is often a toroidally wrapped ring or a pair of linear elements whose drive windings are each wound in opposing directions.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Such closed flux paths minimise coupling between the drive and sense windings.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In the presence of an external magnetic field, with the core in a highly permeable state, such a field is locally attracted or gated (hence the name fluxgate) through the sense winding.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] When the core is weakly permeable, the external field is less attracted.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This continuous gating of the external field in and out of the sense winding induces a signal in the sense winding, whose principal frequency is twice that of the drive frequency, and whose strength and phase orientation vary directly with the external-field magnitude and polarity.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] There are additional factors that affect the size of the resultant signal.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] These factors include the number of turns in the sense winding, magnetic permeability of the core, sensor geometry, and the gated flux rate of change with respect to time.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Phase synchronous detection is used to extract these harmonic signals from the sense winding and convert them into a DC voltage proportional to the external magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Active current feedback may also be employed, such that the sense winding is driven to counteract the external field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In such cases, the feedback current varies linearly with the external magnetic field and is used as the basis for measurement.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This helps to counter inherent non-linearity between the applied external field strength and the flux gated through the sense winding.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] SQUIDs, or superconducting quantum interference devices, measure extremely small changes in magnetic fields.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] They are very sensitive vector magnetometers, with noise levels as low as 3 fT⋅Hz−1/2 in commercial instruments and 0.4 fT⋅Hz−1/2 in experimental devices.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Many liquid-helium-cooled commercial SQUIDs achieve a flat noise spectrum from near DC (less than 1 Hz) to tens of kilohertz, making such devices ideal for time-domain biomagnetic signal measurements.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] SERF atomic magnetometers demonstrated in laboratories so far reach competitive noise floor but in relatively small frequency ranges.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] SQUID magnetometers require cooling with liquid helium (4.2 K) or liquid nitrogen (77 K) to operate, hence the packaging requirements to use them are rather stringent both from a thermal-mechanical as well as magnetic standpoint.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] SQUID magnetometers are most commonly used to measure the magnetic fields produced by laboratory samples, also for brain or heart activity (magnetoencephalography and magnetocardiography, respectively).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Geophysical surveys use SQUIDs from time to time, but the logistics of cooling the SQUID are much more complicated than other magnetometers that operate at room temperature.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Magnetometers based on atomic gasses can perform vector measurements of the magnetic field in the low field regime, where the decay of the atomic coherence becomes faster than the Larmor frequency.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The physics of such magnetometers is based on the Hanle effect.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Such zero-field optically pumped magnetometers have been tested in various configurations and with different atomic species, notably alkali (potassium, rubidium and cesium), helium and mercury.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] For the case of alkali, the coherence times were greatly limited due to spin-exchange relaxation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] A major breakthrough happened at the beginning of the 2000 decade, Romalis group in Princeton demonstrated that in such a low field regime, alkali coherence times can be greatly enhanced if a high enough density can be reached by high temperature heating, this is the so-called SERF effect.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The main interest of optically-pumped magnetometers is to replace SQUID magnetometers in applications where cryogenic cooling is a drawback.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This is notably the case of medical imaging where such cooling imposes a thick thermal insulation, strongly affecting the amplitude of the recorded biomagnetic signals.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Several startup companies are currently developing optically pumped magnetometers for biomedical applications: those of TwinLeaf, quSpin and FieldLine being based on alkali vapors, and those of Mag4Health on metastable helium-4.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] At sufficiently high atomic density, extremely high sensitivity can be achieved.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Spin-exchange-relaxation-free (SERF) atomic magnetometers containing potassium, caesium, or rubidium vapor operate similarly to the caesium magnetometers described above, yet can reach sensitivities lower than 1 fT⋅Hz−1⁄2.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The SERF magnetometers only operate in small magnetic fields.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The Earth's field is about 50 μT; SERF magnetometers operate in fields less than 0.5 μT.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] Large volume detectors have achieved a sensitivity of 200 aT⋅Hz−1⁄2.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This technology has greater sensitivity per unit volume than SQUID detectors.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The technology can also produce very small magnetometers that may in the future replace coils for detecting radio-frequency magnetic fields.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This technology may produce a magnetic sensor that has all of its input and output signals in the form of light on fiber-optic cables.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] This lets the magnetic measurement be made near high electrical voltages.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] The calibration of magnetometers is usually performed by means of coils which are supplied by an electrical current to create a magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] It allows to characterize the sensitivity of the magnetometer (in terms of V/T).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] In many applications the homogeneity of the calibration coil is an important feature.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] For this reason, coils like Helmholtz coils are commonly used either in a single axis or a three axis configuration.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p01] For demanding applications a high homogeneity magnetic field is mandatory, in such cases magnetic field calibration can be performed using a Maxwell coil, cosine coils, or calibration in the highly homogenous Earth's magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers have a very diverse range of applications, including locating objects such as submarines, sunken ships, hazards affecting tunnel boring machines, coal mine hazards, unexploded ordnance, toxic waste drums, as well as a wide range of mineral deposits and geological structures.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Laboratory magnetometers determine the magnetic dipole moment of a magnetic sample, typically as a function of temperature, magnetic field, or other parameter.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] This helps to reveal its magnetic properties such as ferromagnetism, antiferromagnetism, superconductivity, or other properties that affect magnetism.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers are used to measure or monitor mechanical stress in ferromagnetic materials.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Mechanical stress will improve alignment of magnetic domains in microscopic scale that will raise the magnetic field measured close to the material by magnetometers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] There are different hypothesis about stress-magnetisation relationship.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] However the effect of mechanical stress on measured magnetic field near the specimen is claimed to be proven in many scientific publications.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] There have been efforts to solve the inverse problem of magnetisation-stress resolution in order to quantify the stress based on measured magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers are used extensively in experimental particle physics to measure the magnetic field of pivotal components such as the concentration or focusing beam-magnets.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers are also used to detect archaeological sites, shipwrecks, and other buried or submerged objects.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Fluxgate gradiometers are popular due to their compact configuration and relatively low cost.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Gradiometers enhance shallow features and negate the need for a base station.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Caesium and Overhauser magnetometers are also very effective when used as gradiometers or as single-sensor systems with base stations.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The TV program *Time Team* popularised 'geophys', including magnetic techniques used in archaeological work to detect fire hearths, walls of baked bricks and magnetic stones such as basalt and granite.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Walking tracks and roadways can sometimes be mapped with differential compaction in magnetic soils or with disturbances in clays, such as on the Great Hungarian Plain.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Ploughed fields behave as sources of magnetic noise in such surveys.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers can give an indication of auroral activity before the light from the aurora becomes visible.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] A grid of magnetometers around the world constantly measures the effect of the solar wind on the Earth's magnetic field, which is then published on the K-index.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] While magnetometers can be used to help map basin shape at a regional scale, they are more commonly used to map hazards to coal mining, such as basaltic intrusions (dykes, sills, and volcanic plug) that destroy resources and are dangerous to longwall mining equipment.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers can also locate zones ignited by lightning and map siderite (an impurity in coal).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The best survey results are achieved on the ground in high-resolution surveys (with approximately 10 m line spacing and 0.5 m station spacing).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Bore-hole magnetometers using a Ferretcan also assist when coal seams are deep, by using multiple sills or looking beneath surface basalt flows.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Modern surveys generally use magnetometers with GPS technology to automatically record the magnetic field and their location.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The data set is then corrected with data from a second magnetometer (the base station) that is left stationary and records the change in the Earth's magnetic field during the survey.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers are used in directional drilling for oil or gas to detect the azimuth of the drilling tools near the drill.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] They are most often paired with accelerometers in drilling tools so that both the inclination and azimuth of the drill can be found.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] For defensive purposes, navies use arrays of magnetometers laid across sea floors in strategic locations (i.e. around ports) to monitor submarine activity.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The Russian Alfa-class titanium submarines were designed and built at great expense to thwart such systems (as pure titanium is non-magnetic).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Military submarines are degaussed—by passing through large underwater loops at regular intervals—to help them escape detection by sea-floor monitoring systems, magnetic anomaly detectors, and magnetically-triggered mines.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] However, submarines are never completely de-magnetised.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] It is possible to tell the depth at which a submarine has been by measuring its magnetic field, which is distorted as the pressure distorts the hull and hence the field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Heating can also change the magnetization of steel.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Submarines tow long sonar arrays to detect ships, and can even recognise different propeller noises.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The sonar arrays need to be accurately positioned so they can triangulate direction to targets (e.g. ships).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The arrays do not tow in a straight line, so fluxgate magnetometers are used to orient each sonar node in the array.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Fluxgates can also be used in weapons navigation systems, but have been largely superseded by GPS and ring laser gyroscopes.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers such as the German Foerster are used to locate ferrous ordnance.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Caesium and Overhauser magnetometers are used to locate and help clean up old bombing and test ranges.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] UAV payloads also include magnetometers for a range of defensive and offensive tasks.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometric surveys can be useful in defining magnetic anomalies which represent ore (direct detection), or in some cases gangue minerals associated with ore deposits (indirect or inferential detection).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] This includes iron ore, magnetite, hematite, and often pyrrhotite.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Developed countries such as Australia, Canada and USA invest heavily in systematic airborne magnetic surveys of their respective continents and surrounding oceans, to assist with map geology and in the discovery of mineral deposits.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Such aeromag surveys are typically undertaken with 400 m line spacing at 100 m elevation, with readings every 10 meters or more.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] To overcome the asymmetry in the data density, data is interpolated between lines (usually 5 times) and data along the line is then averaged.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Such data is gridded to an 80 m × 80 m pixel size and image processed using a program like ERMapper.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] At an exploration lease scale, the survey may be followed by a more detailed helimag or crop duster style fixed wing at 50 m line spacing and 50 m elevation (terrain permitting).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Such an image is gridded on a 10 m × 10 m pixel, offering 64 times the resolution.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Where targets are shallow (< 200 m), aeromag anomalies may be followed up with ground magnetic surveys on 10 m to 50 m line spacing with 1 m station spacing to provide the best detail (2 to 10 m pixel grid) (or 25 times the resolution prior to drilling).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetic fields from magnetic bodies of ore fall off with the inverse distance cubed (dipole target), or at best inverse distance squared (magnetic monopole target).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] One analogy to the resolution-with-distance is a car driving at night with lights on.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] At a distance of 400 m one sees one glowing haze, but as it approaches, two headlights, and then the left blinker, are visible.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] There are many challenges interpreting magnetic data for mineral exploration.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Multiple targets mix together like multiple heat sources and, unlike light, there is no magnetic telescope to focus fields.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The combination of multiple sources is measured at the surface.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The geometry, depth, or magnetisation direction (remanence) of the targets are also generally not known, and so multiple models can explain the data.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Potent by Geophysical Software Solutions is a leading magnetic (and gravity) interpretation package used extensively in the Australian exploration industry.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers assist mineral explorers both directly (i.e., gold mineralisation associated with magnetite, diamonds in kimberlite pipes) and, more commonly, indirectly, such as by mapping geological structures conducive to mineralisation (i.e., shear zones and alteration haloes around granites).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Airborne Magnetometers detect the change in the Earth's magnetic field using sensors attached to the aircraft in the form of a "stinger" or by towing a magnetometer on the end of a cable.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The magnetometer on a cable is often referred to as a "bomb" because of its shape.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Because hills and valleys under the aircraft make the magnetic readings rise and fall, a radar altimeter keeps track of the transducer's deviation from the nominal altitude above ground.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] There may also be a camera that takes photos of the ground.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The location of the measurement is determined by also recording a GPS.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Many smartphones contain miniaturized microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) magnetometers, which are used to detect magnetic field strength and are used as compasses.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The iPhone 3GS has a magnetometer, a magnetoresistive permalloy sensor, the AN-203 produced by Honeywell.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] In 2009, the price of three-axis magnetometers dipped below US$1 per device and dropped rapidly.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The use of a three-axis device means that it is not sensitive to the way it is held in orientation or elevation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Researchers at Deutsche Telekom have used magnetometers embedded in mobile devices to permit touchless 3D interaction.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Their interaction framework, called MagiTact, tracks changes to the magnetic field around a cellphone to identify different gestures made by a hand holding or wearing a magnet.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Seismic methods are preferred to magnetometers as the primary survey method for oil exploration although magnetic methods can give additional information about the underlying geology and in some environments evidence of leakage from traps.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers are also used in oil exploration to show locations of geologic features that make drilling impractical, and other features that give geophysicists a more complete picture of stratigraphy.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] A three-axis fluxgate magnetometer was part of the *Mariner 2* and *Mariner 10* missions.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] A dual technique magnetometer is part of the *Cassini–Huygens* mission to explore Saturn.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] This system is composed of a vector helium and fluxgate magnetometers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers were also a component instrument on the Mercury *MESSENGER* mission.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] A magnetometer can also be used by satellites like GOES to measure both the magnitude and direction of the magnetic field of a planet or moon.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Systematic surveys can be used to in searching for mineral deposits or locating lost objects.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Aeromag datasets for Australia can be downloaded from the GADDS database.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Data can be divided in point located and image data, the latter of which is in ERMapper format.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] On the base of space measured distribution of magnetic field parameters (e.g. amplitude or direction), the magnetovision images may be generated.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Such presentation of magnetic data is very useful for further analyse and data fusion.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetic gradiometers are pairs of magnetometers with their sensors separated, usually horizontally, by a fixed distance.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The readings are subtracted to measure the difference between the sensed magnetic fields, which gives the field gradients caused by magnetic anomalies.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] This is one way of compensating both for the variability in time of the Earth's magnetic field and for other sources of electromagnetic interference, thus allowing for more sensitive detection of anomalies.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Because nearly equal values are being subtracted, the noise performance requirements for the magnetometers is more extreme.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Gradiometers enhance shallow magnetic anomalies and are thus good for archaeological and site investigation work.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] They are also good for real-time work such as unexploded ordnance (UXO) location.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] It is twice as efficient to run a base station and use two (or more) mobile sensors to read parallel lines simultaneously (assuming data is stored and post-processed).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] In this manner, both along-line and cross-line gradients can be calculated.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] In traditional mineral exploration and archaeological work, grid pegs placed by theodolite and tape measure were used to define the survey area.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Some UXO surveys used ropes to define the lanes.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Airborne surveys used radio triangulation beacons, such as Siledus.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Non-magnetic electronic hipchain triggers were developed to trigger magnetometers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] They used rotary shaft encoders to measure distance along disposable cotton reels.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Modern explorers use a range of low-magnetic signature GPS units, including real-time kinematic GPS.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetic surveys can suffer from noise coming from a range of sources.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Different magnetometer technologies suffer different kinds of noise problems.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Some total field sensors give different readings depending on their orientation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetic materials in the sensor itself are the primary cause of this error.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] In some magnetometers, such as the vapor magnetometers (caesium, potassium, etc.), there are sources of heading error in the physics that contribute small amounts to the total heading error.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Console noise comes from magnetic components on or within the console.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] These include ferrite in cores in inductors and transformers, steel frames around LCDs, legs on IC chips and steel cases in disposable batteries.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Some popular MIL spec connectors also have steel springs.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Operators must take care to be magnetically clean and should check the 'magnetic hygiene' of all apparel and items carried during a survey.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Akubra hats are very popular in Australia, but their steel rims must be removed before use on magnetic surveys.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Steel rings on notepads, steel capped boots and steel springs in overall eyelets can all cause unnecessary noise in surveys.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Pens, mobile phones and stainless steel implants can also be problematic.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The magnetic response (noise) from ferrous object on the operator and console can change with heading direction because of induction and remanence.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Aeromagnetic survey aircraft and quad bike systems can use special compensators to correct for heading error noise.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Heading errors look like herringbone patterns in survey images.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Recording data and image processing is superior to real-time work because subtle anomalies often missed by the operator (especially in magnetically noisy areas) can be correlated between lines, shapes and clusters better defined.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] A range of sophisticated enhancement techniques can also be used.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] There is also a hard copy and need for systematic coverage.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] The Magnetometer Navigation (MAGNAV) algorithm was initially running as a flight experiment in 2004.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Later on, diamond magnetometers were developed by the United States Air Force Research Laboratory (AFRL) as a better method of navigation which cannot be jammed by the enemy.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Magnetometers are used in magnetoencephalography (MEG), a technique that records the weak neuromagnetic fields generated by currents in the brain.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] Existing MEG systems use cryogenically cooled SQUID magnetometers, while newer OPM sensors operate at or near room temperature and can be placed within millimeters of the subject's scalp, enabling wearable systems with improved signal strength and greater tolerance to movement.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/fluxgate-magnetometer-p02] OPM-MEG has been used to measure brain activity in patients with Schizophrenia, Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, Dystonia, Autism, ADHD, and Epilepsy.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The effect is observed as a significant change in the electrical resistance depending on whether the magnetization of adjacent ferromagnetic layers are in a parallel or an antiparallel alignment.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The overall resistance is relatively low for parallel alignment and relatively high for antiparallel alignment.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The magnetization direction can be controlled, for example, by applying an external magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The effect is based on the dependence of electron scattering on spin orientation.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The main application of GMR is in magnetic field sensors, which are used to read data in hard disk drives, biosensors, microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) and other devices.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] GMR multilayer structures are also used in magnetoresistive random-access memory (MRAM) as cells that store one bit of information.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In literature, the term giant magnetoresistance is sometimes confused with colossal magnetoresistance of ferromagnetic and antiferromagnetic semiconductors, which is not related to a multilayer structure.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Magnetoresistance is the dependence of the electrical resistance of a sample on the strength of an external magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] where R(H) is the resistance of the sample in a magnetic field H, and R(0) corresponds to H = 0.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Alternative forms of this expression may use electrical resistivity instead of resistance, a different sign for δH, and are sometimes normalized by R(H) rather than R(0).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The term "giant magnetoresistance" indicates that the value δH for multilayer structures significantly exceeds the anisotropic magnetoresistance, which has a typical value within a few percent.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] GMR was discovered in 1988 independently by the groups of Albert Fert of the University of Paris-Sud, France, and Peter Grünberg of Forschungszentrum Jülich, Germany.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The practical significance of this experimental discovery was recognized by the Nobel Prize in Physics awarded to Fert and Grünberg in 2007.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The first mathematical model describing the effect of magnetization on the mobility of charge carriers in solids, related to the spin of those carriers, was reported in 1936.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Experimental evidence of the potential enhancement of δH has been known since the 1960s.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] By the late 1980s, the anisotropic magnetoresistance had been well explored, but the corresponding value of δH did not exceed a few percent.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The enhancement of δH became possible with the advent of sample preparation techniques such as molecular beam epitaxy, which allows manufacturing multilayer thin films with a thickness of several nanometers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Fert and Grünberg studied electrical resistance of structures incorporating ferromagnetic and non-ferromagnetic materials.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In particular, Fert worked on multilayer films, and Grünberg in 1986 discovered the antiferromagnetic exchange interaction in Fe/Cr films.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The GMR discovery work was carried out by the two groups on slightly different samples.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The Fert group used (001)Fe/(001) Cr superlattices wherein the Fe and Cr layers were deposited in a high vacuum on a (001) GaAs substrate kept at 20 °C and the magnetoresistance measurements were taken at low temperature (typically 4.2 K).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The Grünberg work was performed on multilayers of Fe and Cr on (110) GaAs at room temperature.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Changing the thickness of the non-magnetic layers led to a significant reduction of the residual magnetization in the hysteresis loop.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Electrical resistance changed by up to 50% with the external magnetic field at 4.2 K.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Fert named the new effect giant magnetoresistance, to highlight its difference with the anisotropic magnetoresistance.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The Grünberg experiment made the same discovery but the effect was less pronounced (3% compared to 50%) due to the samples being at room temperature rather than low temperature.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The discoverers suggested that the effect is based on spin-dependent scattering of electrons in the superlattice, particularly on the dependence of resistance of the layers on the relative orientations of magnetization and electron spins.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The theory of GMR for different directions of the current was developed in the next few years.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In 1989, Camley and Barnaś calculated the "current in plane" (CIP) geometry, where the current flows along the layers, in the classical approximation, whereas Levy *et al.* used the quantum formalism.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The theory of the GMR for the current perpendicular to the layers (current perpendicular to the plane or CPP geometry), known as the Valet-Fert theory, was reported in 1993.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Applications favor the CPP geometry because it provides a greater magnetoresistance ratio (δH), thus resulting in a greater device sensitivity.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In magnetically ordered materials, the electrical resistance is crucially affected by scattering of electrons on the magnetic sublattice of the crystal, which is formed by crystallographically equivalent atoms with nonzero magnetic moments.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Scattering depends on the relative orientations of the electron spins and those magnetic moments: it is weakest when they are parallel and strongest when they are antiparallel; it is relatively strong in the paramagnetic state, in which the magnetic moments of the atoms have random orientations.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] For good conductors such as gold or copper, the Fermi level lies within the *sp* band, and the *d* band is completely filled.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In ferromagnets, the dependence of electron-atom scattering on the orientation of their magnetic moments is related to the filling of the band responsible for the magnetic properties of the metal, e.g., 3*d* band for iron, nickel or cobalt.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The *d* band of ferromagnets is split, as it contains a different number of electrons with spins directed up and down.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Therefore, the density of electronic states at the Fermi level is also different for spins pointing in opposite directions.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The Fermi level for majority-spin electrons is located within the *sp* band, and their transport is similar in ferromagnets and non-magnetic metals.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] For minority-spin electrons the *sp* and *d* bands are hybridized, and the Fermi level lies within the *d* band.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The hybridized *spd* band has a high density of states, which results in stronger scattering and thus shorter mean free path λ for minority-spin than majority-spin electrons.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In cobalt-doped nickel, the ratio λ↑/λ↓ can reach 20.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] According to the Drude theory, the conductivity is proportional to λ, which ranges from several to several tens of nanometers in thin metal films.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Electrons "remember" the direction of spin within the so-called spin relaxation length (or spin diffusion length), which can significantly exceed the mean free path.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Spin-dependent transport refers to the dependence of electrical conductivity on the spin direction of the charge carriers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In ferromagnets, it occurs due to electron transitions between the unsplit 4*s* and split 3*d* bands.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In some materials, the interaction between electrons and atoms is the weakest when their magnetic moments are antiparallel rather than parallel.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] A combination of both types of materials can result in a so-called inverse GMR effect.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Electric current can be passed through magnetic superlattices in two ways.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In the current in plane (CIP) geometry, the current flows along the layers, and the electrodes are located on one side of the structure.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In the current perpendicular to plane (CPP) configuration, the current is passed perpendicular to the layers, and the electrodes are located on different sides of the superlattice.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The CPP geometry results in more than twice higher GMR, but is more difficult to realize in practice than the CIP configuration.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Magnetic ordering differs in superlattices with ferromagnetic and antiferromagnetic interaction between the layers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In the former case, the magnetization directions are the same in different ferromagnetic layers in the absence of applied magnetic field, whereas in the latter case, opposite directions alternate in the multilayer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Electrons traveling through the ferromagnetic superlattice interact with it much weaker when their spin directions are opposite to the magnetization of the lattice than when they are parallel to it.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Such anisotropy is not observed for the antiferromagnetic superlattice; as a result, it scatters electrons stronger than the ferromagnetic superlattice and exhibits a higher electrical resistance.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Applications of the GMR effect require dynamic switching between the parallel and antiparallel magnetization of the layers in a superlattice.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The coefficient *J* is an oscillatory function of the thickness of the non-magnetic layer ds; therefore *J* can change its magnitude and sign.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] If the ds value corresponds to the antiparallel state then an external field can switch the superlattice from the antiparallel state (high resistance) to the parallel state (low resistance).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] where R0 is the resistance of ferromagnetic superlattice, ΔR is the GMR increment and θ is the angle between the magnetizations of adjacent layers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The GMR phenomenon can be described using two spin-related conductivity channels corresponding to the conduction of electrons, for which the resistance is minimum or maximum.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The relation between them is often defined in terms of the coefficient of the spin anisotropy β.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] where *ρF* is the average resistivity of the ferromagnet.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In this model, there are two conduction channels for electrons with various spin directions relative to the magnetization of the layers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Therefore, the equivalent circuit of the GMR structure consists of two parallel connections corresponding to each of the channels.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Here the subscript of R denote collinear and oppositely oriented magnetization in layers, *χ = b/a* is the thickness ratio of the magnetic and non-magnetic layers, and ρN is the resistivity of non-magnetic metal.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] This expression is applicable for both CIP and CPP structures.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Such a device, with resistance depending on the orientation of electron spin, is called a spin valve.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] It is "open", if the magnetizations of its layers are parallel, and "closed" otherwise.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In 1993, Thierry Valet and Albert Fert presented a model for the giant magnetoresistance in the CPP geometry, based on the Boltzmann equations.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In this model the chemical potential inside the magnetic layer is split into two functions, corresponding to electrons with spins parallel and antiparallel to the magnetization of the layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] where *ℓ*s is the average length of spin relaxation, and the z coordinate is measured from the boundary between the magnetic and non-magnetic layers (z < 0 corresponds to the ferromagnetic).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Thus electrons with a larger chemical potential will accumulate at the boundary of the ferromagnet.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] where *j* is current density in the sample, *ℓ*sN and *ℓ*sF are the length of the spin relaxation in a non-magnetic and magnetic materials, respectively.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The magnetoresistance depends on many parameters such as the geometry of the device (CIP or CPP), its temperature, and the thicknesses of ferromagnetic and non-magnetic layers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] At a temperature of 4.2 K and a thickness of cobalt layers of 1.5 nm, increasing the thickness of copper layers dCu from 1 to 10 nm decreased δH from 80 to 10% in the CIP geometry.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Meanwhile, in the CPP geometry the maximum of δH (125%) was observed for dCu = 2.5 nm, and increasing dCu to 10 nm reduced δH to 60% in an oscillating manner.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] When a Co(1.2 nm)/Cu(1.1 nm) superlattice was heated from near zero to 300 K, its δH decreased from 40 to 20% in the CIP geometry, and from 100 to 55% in the CPP geometry.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The non-magnetic layers can be non-metallic.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] For example, δH up to 40% was demonstrated for organic layers at 11 K.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Graphene spin valves of various designs exhibited δH of about 12% at 7 K and 10% at 300 K, far below the theoretical limit of 109%.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The GMR effect can be enhanced by spin filters that select electrons with a certain spin orientation; they are made of metals such as cobalt.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] where ΔGSV is change in the conductivity of the spin valve without the filter, ΔGf is the maximum increase in conductivity with the filter, and β is a parameter of the filter material.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] GMR is often classed by the type of devices which exhibit the effect.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] GMR in films was first observed by Fert and Grünberg in a study of superlattices composed of ferromagnetic and non-magnetic layers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The thickness of the non-magnetic layers was chosen such that the interaction between the layers was antiferromagnetic and the magnetization in adjacent magnetic layers was antiparallel.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Then an external magnetic field could make the magnetization vectors parallel thereby affecting the electrical resistance of the structure.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Magnetic layers in such structures interact through antiferromagnetic coupling, which results in the oscillating dependence of the GMR on the thickness of the non-magnetic layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In the first magnetic field sensors using antiferromagnetic superlattices, the saturation field was very large, up to tens of thousands of oersteds, due to the strong antiferromagnetic interaction between their layers (made of chromium, iron or cobalt) and the strong anisotropy fields in them.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Therefore, the sensitivity of the devices was very low.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The use of permalloy for the magnetic and silver for the non-magnetic layers lowered the saturation field to tens of oersteds.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In the most successful spin valves the GMR effect originates from exchange bias.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] They comprise a sensitive layer, "fixed" layer and an antiferromagnetic layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The last layer freezes the magnetization direction in the "fixed" layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The sensitive and antiferromagnetic layers are made thin to reduce the resistance of the structure.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The valve reacts to the external magnetic field by changing the magnetization direction in the sensitive layer relatively to the "fixed" layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] where δH0 is a normalization constant, λN is the mean free path of electrons in the non-magnetic material, *d*0 is effective thickness that includes interaction between layers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The parameters have the same meaning as in the previous equation, but they now refer to the ferromagnetic layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] GMR can also be observed in the absence of antiferromagnetic coupling layers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In this case, the magnetoresistance results from the differences in the coercive forces (for example, it is smaller for permalloy than cobalt).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In multilayers such as permalloy/Cu/Co/Cu the external magnetic field switches the direction of saturation magnetization to parallel in strong fields and to antiparallel in weak fields.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Such systems exhibit a lower saturation field and a larger δH than superlattices with antiferromagnetic coupling.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] A similar effect is observed in Co/Cu structures.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The existence of these structures means that GMR does not require interlayer coupling, and can originate from a distribution of the magnetic moments that can be controlled by an external field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In the inverse GMR, the resistance is minimum for the antiparallel orientation of the magnetization in the layers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Inverse GMR is observed when the magnetic layers are composed of different materials, such as NiCr/Cu/Co/Cu.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The resistivity for electrons with opposite spins can be written as $\rho _{\uparrow ,\downarrow }={\frac {2\rho _{F}}{1\pm \beta }}$ ; it has different values, i.e. different coefficients β, for spin-up and spin-down electrons.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] If the NiCr layer is not too thin, its contribution may exceed that of the Co layer, resulting in inverse GMR.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Note that the GMR inversion depends on the sign of the *product* of the coefficients β in adjacent ferromagnetic layers, but not on the signs of individual coefficients.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Inverse GMR is also observed if NiCr alloy is replaced by vanadium-doped nickel, but not for doping of nickel with iron, cobalt, manganese, gold or copper.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] GMR in granular alloys of ferromagnetic and non-magnetic metals was discovered in 1992 and subsequently explained by the spin-dependent scattering of charge carriers at the surface and in the bulk of the grains.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The grains form ferromagnetic clusters about 10 nm in diameter embedded in a non-magnetic metal, forming a kind of superlattice.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] A necessary condition for the GMR effect in such structures is poor mutual solubility in its components (e.g., cobalt and copper).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Their properties strongly depend on the measurement and annealing temperature.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] One of the main applications of GMR materials is in magnetic field sensors, e.g., in hard disk drives and biosensors, as well as detectors of oscillations in MEMS.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The binder and protective layers are often made of tantalum, and a typical non-magnetic material is copper.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In the sensing layer, magnetization can be reoriented by the external magnetic field; it is typically made of NiFe or cobalt alloys.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] FeMn or NiMn can be used for the antiferromagnetic layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The fixed layer is made of a magnetic material such as cobalt.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Such a sensor has an asymmetric hysteresis loop owing to the presence of the magnetically hard, fixed layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Spin valves may exhibit anisotropic magnetoresistance, which leads to an asymmetry in the sensitivity curve.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In hard disk drives (HDDs), information is encoded using magnetic domains, and a change in the direction of their magnetization is associated with the logical level 1 while no change represents a logical 0.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] There are two recording methods: longitudinal and perpendicular.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In the longitudinal method, the magnetization is parallel to the surface.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] A transition region (domain walls) is formed between domains, in which the magnetic field exits the material.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] If the domain wall is located at the interface of two north-pole domains then the field is directed outward, and for two south-pole domains it is directed inward.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] To read the direction of the magnetic field above the domain wall, the magnetization direction is fixed normal to the surface in the antiferromagnetic layer and parallel to the surface in the sensing layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Changing the direction of the external magnetic field deflects the magnetization in the sensing layer.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] When the field tends to align the magnetizations in the sensing and fixed layers, the electrical resistance of the sensor decreases, and vice versa.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] A cell of magnetoresistive random-access memory (MRAM) has a structure similar to the spin-valve sensor.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The value of the stored bits can be encoded via the magnetization direction in the sensor layer; it is read by measuring the resistance of the structure.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The advantages of this technology are independence of power supply (the information is preserved when the power is switched off owing to the potential barrier for reorienting the magnetization), low power consumption and high speed.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In a typical GMR-based storage unit, a CIP structure is located between two wires oriented perpendicular to each other.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] These conductors are called lines of rows and columns.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Pulses of electric current passing through the lines generate a vortex magnetic field, which affects the GMR structure.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The field lines have ellipsoid shapes, and the field direction (clockwise or counterclockwise) is determined by the direction of the current in the line.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In the GMR structure, the magnetization is oriented along the line.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] The direction of the field produced by the line of the column is almost parallel to the magnetic moments, and it can not reorient them.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Line of the row is perpendicular, and regardless of the magnitude of the field can rotate the magnetization by only 90°.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] With the simultaneous passage of pulses along the row and column lines, of the total magnetic field at the location of the GMR structure will be directed at an acute angle with respect to one point and an obtuse to others.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] If the value of the field exceeds some critical value, the latter changes its direction.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] There are several storage and reading methods for the described cell.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In one method, the information is stored in the sensing layer; it is read via resistance measurement and is erased upon reading.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] In another scheme, the information is kept in the fixed layer, which requires higher recording currents compared to reading currents.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Tunnel magnetoresistance (TMR) is an extension of spin-valve GMR, in which the electrons travel with their spins oriented perpendicularly to the layers across a thin insulating tunnel barrier (replacing the non-ferromagnetic spacer).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] This allows to achieve a larger impedance, a larger magnetoresistance value (~10× at room temperature) and a negligible temperature dependence.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] TMR has now replaced GMR in MRAMs and disk drives, in particular for high area densities and perpendicular recording.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Magnetoresistive insulators for contactless signal transmission between two electrically isolated parts of electrical circuits were first demonstrated in 1997 as an alternative to opto-isolators.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] A Wheatstone bridge of four identical GMR devices is insensitive to a uniform magnetic field and reacts only when the field directions are antiparallel in the neighboring arms of the bridge.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/giant-magnetoresistance] Such devices were reported in 2003 and may be used as rectifiers with a linear frequency response.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The **Hall effect** is the production of a potential difference, across an electrical conductor, that is transverse to an electric current in the conductor and to an applied magnetic field perpendicular to the current.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Such potential difference is known as the **Hall voltage**.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] It was discovered by Edwin Hall in 1879 through a study of the electromagnetic theory of James Clerk Maxwell, becoming a critical confirmation of that theory.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The **Hall coefficient** is defined as the ratio of the induced electric field to the product of the current density and the applied magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] It is a characteristic of the material from which the conductor is made, since its value depends on the type, number, and properties of the charge carriers that constitute the current.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Wires carrying current in a magnetic field experience a mechanical force perpendicular to both the current and magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] In the 1820s, André-Marie Ampère observed this underlying mechanism that led to the discovery of the Hall effect.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] However it was not until a solid mathematical basis for electromagnetism was systematized by James Clerk Maxwell's "On Physical Lines of Force" (published in 1861–1862) that details of the interaction between magnets and electric current could be understood.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Edwin Hall then explored the question of whether magnetic fields interacted with the conductors *or* the electric current, and reasoned that if the force was specifically acting on the current, it should crowd current to one side of the wire, producing a small measurable voltage.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] In 1879, he discovered this *Hall effect* while he was working on his doctoral degree at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Eighteen years before the electron was discovered, his measurements of the tiny effect produced in the apparatus he used were an experimental tour de force, published under the name "On a New Action of the Magnet on Electric Currents".
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The Hall effect is due to the nature of the current in a conductor.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Current consists of the movement of many small charge carriers, typically electrons, holes, ions (see Electromigration) or all three.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] When a magnetic field is present, these charges experience a force, called the Lorentz force.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] When such a magnetic field is absent, the charges follow approximately straight paths between collisions with impurities, phonons, etc.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] However, when a magnetic field with a perpendicular component is applied, their paths between collisions are curved; thus, moving charges accumulate on one face of the material.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] This leaves equal and opposite charges exposed on the other face, where there is a scarcity of mobile charges.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The result is an asymmetric distribution of charge density across the Hall element, arising from a force that is perpendicular to both the straight path and the applied magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The separation of charge establishes an electric field that opposes the migration of further charge, so a steady electric potential is established for as long as the charge is flowing.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] In classical electromagnetism, electrons move in the opposite direction of the current *I* (by convention "current" describes a theoretical "hole flow").
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] In some metals and semiconductors it *appears* "holes" are actually flowing because the direction of the voltage is opposite to the derivation below.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The Hall voltage *V*H can be derived for a conductor with only one type of charge carrier such as a simple metal with delocalised electrons.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Charges that move in an electromagnetic field are affected by the Lorentz Force ${\vec {F}}_{L}$ . ${\vec {F}}_{L}=q\,({\vec {v}}\times {\vec {B}})$ With the velocity of the charge carriers ${\vec {v}}$ , the electric charge of said carriers q and the magnetic field ${\vec {B}}$ .
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] As charges accumulate towards one side of the carrier due to the Lorentz Force, a charge imbalance and hence an electric field ${\vec {E}}$ builds up, itself acting upon the charges $F_{E}=-q\cdot {\vec {E}}$ .
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Inserting this into the equation yields: $E_{y}={\frac {j_{x}}{nq}}\cdot B_{z}$ A material and temperature dependent Hall Coefficient $R_{H}$ is defined $E_{y}=R_{H}j_{x}B_{z}$ .
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] To get the Voltage, one can use the same relation as in capacitors $E_{y}={\frac {V_{H}}{W}}$ with W the width of the conductor (refer to the figure above).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Furthermore, the current density is the current divided by the cross-section.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] For our cubic conductor, this is $j_{x}={\frac {I_{x}}{dW}}$ with the thickness d .
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Rearranging the relation then gives: $V_{H}=R_{H}{\frac {I_{x}B_{z}}{d}}$ This relationship remains the same for more complicated conductors with different charge carriers, however the calculation of the Hall Constant is more complicated for those.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Notice through the diagram that no matter the sign of the charge carrier, it get's deflected in the same direction.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The polarity of the Hall voltage however would be reversed as a positively charged field would build up in case of positive charge carriers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] This property of the Hall effect offered the first real proof that electric currents in most metals are carried by moving electrons, not by protons.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] It also showed that in some substances (especially p-type semiconductors), it is contrarily more appropriate to think of the current as positive "holes" moving rather than negative electrons.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] A common source of confusion with the Hall effect in such materials is that holes moving one way are really electrons moving the opposite way, so one expects the Hall voltage polarity to be the same as if electrons were the charge carriers as in most metals and n-type semiconductors.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Yet we observe the opposite polarity of Hall voltage, indicating positive charge carriers.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] However, of course there are no actual positrons or other positive elementary particles carrying the charge in p-type semiconductors, hence the name "holes".
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Unrelatedly, inhomogeneity in the conductive sample can result in a spurious sign of the Hall effect, even in ideal van der Pauw configuration of electrodes.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] For example, a Hall effect consistent with positive carriers was observed in evidently n-type semiconductors.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Another source of artefact, in uniform materials, occurs when the sample's aspect ratio is not long enough: the full Hall voltage only develops far away from the current-introducing contacts, since at the contacts the transverse voltage is shorted out to zero.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] When a current-carrying semiconductor is kept in a magnetic field, the charge carriers of the semiconductor experience a force in a direction perpendicular to both the magnetic field and the current.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] At equilibrium, a voltage appears at the semiconductor edges.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The simple formula for the Hall coefficient given above is usually a good explanation when conduction is dominated by a single charge carrier.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] However, in semiconductors and many metals the theory is more complex, because in these materials conduction can involve significant, simultaneous contributions from both electrons and holes, which may be present in different concentrations and have different mobilities.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] For large applied fields the simpler expression analogous to that for a single carrier type holds.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Although it is well known that magnetic fields play an important role in star formation, research models indicate that Hall diffusion critically influences the dynamics of gravitational collapse that forms protostars.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] For a two-dimensional electron system which can be produced in a MOSFET, in the presence of large magnetic field strength and low temperature, one can observe the quantum Hall effect, in which the Hall conductance σ undergoes quantum Hall transitions to take on quantized values.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The spin Hall effect consists in the spin accumulation on the lateral boundaries of a current-carrying sample.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] It was predicted by Mikhail Dyakonov and V.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Perel in 1971 and observed experimentally more than 30 years later, both in semiconductors and in metals, at cryogenic as well as at room temperatures.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Where $j_{s}$ is the spin current generated by the applied current density $j_{e}$ .
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] For mercury telluride two dimensional quantum wells with strong spin-orbit coupling, in zero magnetic field, at low temperature, the quantum spin Hall effect has been observed in 2007.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] (Note that this effect is *not* due to the contribution of the magnetization to the total magnetic field.) For example, in nickel, the anomalous Hall coefficient is about 100 times larger than the ordinary Hall coefficient near the Curie temperature, but the two are similar at very low temperatures.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Although a well-recognized phenomenon, there is still debate about its origins in the various materials.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The anomalous Hall effect can be either an *extrinsic* (disorder-related) effect due to spin-dependent scattering of the charge carriers, or an *intrinsic* effect which can be described in terms of the Berry phase effect in the crystal momentum space (*k*-space).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The Hall effect in an ionized gas (plasma) is significantly different from the Hall effect in solids (where the **Hall parameter** is always much less than unity).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] In a plasma, the Hall parameter can take any value.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The Hall parameter value increases with the magnetic field strength.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Physically, the trajectories of electrons are curved by the Lorentz force.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Nevertheless, when the Hall parameter is low, their motion between two encounters with heavy particles (neutral or ion) is almost linear.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] But if the Hall parameter is high, the electron movements are highly curved.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The current density vector, **J**, is no longer collinear with the electric field vector, **E**.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The Hall Effects family has expanded to encompass other quasi-particles in semiconductor nanostructures.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Specifically, a set of Hall Effects has emerged based on excitons and exciton-polaritons in 2D materials and quantum wells.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Hall sensors amplify and use the Hall effect for a variety of sensing applications.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Hall-effect thrusters use the Hall effect to limit electrons' axial motion and use them to accelerate a propellant.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The Corbino effect, named after its discoverer Orso Mario Corbino, is a phenomenon involving the Hall effect, but a disc-shaped metal sample is used in place of a rectangular one.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] Because of its shape the Corbino disc allows the observation of Hall effect–based magnetoresistance without the associated Hall voltage.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] A radial current through a circular disc, subjected to a magnetic field perpendicular to the plane of the disc, produces a "circular" current through the disc.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/hall-effect] The absence of the free transverse boundaries renders the interpretation of the Corbino effect simpler than that of the Hall effect.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetometer-p02] Potent by Geophysical Software Solutions [1] is a leading magnetic (and gravity) interpretation package used extensively in the Australian exploration industry.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] The first magnetoresistive effect was discovered in 1856 by William Thomson, better known as Lord Kelvin, but he was unable to lower the electrical resistance of anything by more than 5%.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Today, systems including semimetals and concentric ring EMR structures are known.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] In these, a magnetic field can adjust the resistance by orders of magnitude.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Since different mechanisms can alter the resistance, it is useful to separately consider situations where it depends on a magnetic field directly (e.g. geometric magnetoresistance and multiband magnetoresistance) and those where it does so indirectly through magnetization (e.g.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] William Thomson (Lord Kelvin) first discovered ordinary magnetoresistance in 1856.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] He experimented with pieces of iron and discovered that the resistance increases when the current is in the same direction as the magnetic force and decreases when the current is at 90° to the magnetic force.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] He then did the same experiment with nickel and found that it was affected in the same way but the magnitude of the effect was greater.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] This effect is referred to as anisotropic magnetoresistance (AMR).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] In 2007, Albert Fert and Peter Grünberg were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize for the discovery of giant magnetoresistance.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] An example of magnetoresistance due to direct action of magnetic field on electric current can be studied on a Corbino disc (see Figure).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] It consists of a conducting annulus with perfectly conducting rims.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Without a magnetic field, the battery drives a radial current between the rims.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] When a magnetic field perpendicular to the plane of the annulus is applied, (either into or out of the page) a circular component of current flows as well, due to Lorentz force.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Initial interest in this problem began with Boltzmann in 1886, and independently was re-examined by Corbino in 1911.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] In a simple model, supposing the response to the Lorentz force is the same as for an electric field, the carrier velocity **v** is given by: $\mathbf {v} =\mu \left(\mathbf {E} +\mathbf {v\times B} \right),$ where μ is the carrier mobility.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] where the effective reduction in mobility due to the **B**-field (for motion perpendicular to this field) is apparent.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Electric current (proportional to the radial component of velocity) will decrease with increasing magnetic field and hence the resistance of the device will increase.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Critically, this magnetoresistive scenario depends sensitively on the device geometry and current lines and it does not rely on magnetic materials.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] In a semiconductor with a single carrier type, the magnetoresistance is proportional to (1 + (*μB*)2), where μ is the semiconductor mobility (units m2·V−1·s−1, equivalently m2·Wb−1, or T −1) and B is the magnetic field (units teslas).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Indium antimonide, an example of a high mobility semiconductor, could have an electron mobility above 4 m2/Wb at 300 K.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] So in a 0.25 T field, for example the magnetoresistance increase would be 100%.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Thomson's experiments are an example of AMR, a property of a material in which a dependence of electrical resistance on the angle between the direction of electric current and direction of **magnetization** is observed.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] The effect arises in most cases from the simultaneous action of magnetization and spin–orbit interaction (exceptions related to non-collinear magnetic order notwithstanding) and its detailed mechanism depends on the material.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] It can be for example due to a larger probability of s-d scattering of electrons in the direction of magnetization (which is controlled by the applied magnetic field).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] The net effect (in most materials) is that the electrical resistance has maximum value when the direction of current is parallel to the applied magnetic field.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] AMR of new materials is being investigated and magnitudes up to 50% have been observed in some uranium (but otherwise quite conventional) ferromagnetic compounds.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Materials with extreme AMR have been identified driven by unconventional mechanisms such as a metal-insulator transition triggered by rotating the magnetic moments (while for some directions of magnetic moments, the system is semimetallic, for other directions a gap opens).
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Associated with longitudinal resistivity, there is also transversal resistivity dubbed (somewhat confusingly) the planar Hall effect.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] In monocrystals, resistivity ρ depends also on ψ and θ individually.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] To compensate for the non-linear characteristics and inability to detect the polarity of a magnetic field, the following structure is used for sensors.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] It consists of stripes of aluminum or gold placed on a thin film of permalloy (a ferromagnetic material exhibiting the AMR effect) inclined at an angle of 45°.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] This structure forces the current not to flow along the "easy axes" of thin film, but at an angle of 45°.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] The dependence of resistance now has a permanent offset which is linear around the null point.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Because of its appearance, this sensor type is called 'barber pole'.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] The AMR effect is used in a wide array of sensors for measurement of Earth's magnetic field (electronic compass), for electric current measuring (by measuring the magnetic field created around the conductor), for traffic detection and for linear position and angle sensing.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] The biggest AMR sensor manufacturers are Honeywell, NXP Semiconductors, STMicroelectronics, and Sensitec GmbH.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] Jaoul (*CFJ*) derived an expression of the AMR ratio for Ni-based alloys using the two-current model with s-s and s-d scattering processes, where 's' is a conduction electron, and 'd' is 3d states with the spin-orbit interaction.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] In addition, recently, Satoshi Kokado et al. have obtained the general expression of the AMR ratio for 3d transition-metal ferromagnets by extending the CFJ theory to a more general one.
[src:magnetometer-sensors/magnetoresistance] The general expression can also be applied to half-metals.
